          "items": {
            "preprocessing": "4/7 - Implements downsampling with returned scale factor, Gaussian blur with odd-kernel enforcement, and a form of background subtraction. However the background subtraction is incorrect: it uses MORPH_TOPHAT as 'background' then subtracts it from the original (should typically use opening/closing estimate or use the tophat result directly). Parameters are configurable but the method is not robustly implemented.",
            "coarse_detection": "3/7 - Has contour finding via Canny and uses minEnclosingCircle plus circularity/solidity filters. But it does not implement 'maximum contour detection' (selecting largest/most relevant contour); it sorts candidates by circularity only. Scaling back to original coordinates is done in main, not inside the module (acceptable). Code is incomplete/buggy: candidate comparison relies on dataclass equality and the Hough fallback is truncated.",
            "fine_detection": "3/7 - Implements radial scanning over 360 directions and uses Sobel gradient magnitude to pick a maximum per ray. Dual-edge detector is present but truncated/incomplete, and there is no demonstrated rising/falling edge selection or sub-pixel refinement (only integer pixel selection). FineLocalizer is referenced but not shown, suggesting incomplete integration.",
            "statistical_analysis": "0/7 - RobustStatistics/RadialDataAnalyzer are imported and referenced but the statistical_analysis.py content is not provided here, and there is no visible MAD computation, 3-sigma rejection, or robust radius estimation in the shown code. Cannot verify implementation.",
            "mask_generation": "4/7 - Creates a circular mask correctly and includes chord-adaptive vertical cropping logic based on chord length vs circumference ratio. However chord detection is purely geometric (not from image/gradient), and there is no implemented feature point detection (chord midpoints, high-intensity points, outlier coordinates). Horizontal crop function is truncated and margin handling pads image size rather than generating an in-image margin/dilation mask."
